    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1667"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1667">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/635.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Jefferson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 48.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 8, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Relative to the Department’s desire to secure a
                    frank and full statement covering every phase of the Nicaraguan financial
                    situation as expressed in its telegram of August 17, 1913, and reiterated
                    January 17, 1914, I have the honor to transmit herewith the information<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d1667fn5">Not printed.</note> which I have at length been able
                    to obtain from the President.</p>
                <pb facs="1062" n="946" xml:id="pg_946"/>
                <p>[Explanation of the enclosed financial statements.]</p>
                <p>In view of the chaotic management of the Government’s accounts and the deplorable
                    and almost incomprehensible state of its finances, it can hardly be hoped that
                    the figures here copied are very accurate.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Benjamin L. Jefferson</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
